// @check
// @error-at 19:9 Type `C` is `never` (an empty type — `A & B`, an object and a string literal, have no common values), so it has no values
// `type C = A & B` folds to `never`: an object and a disjoint string literal
// share no values. A real value can never have this type, so the DECLARATION is
// a HARD ERROR even when no value is constructed (PR #189: it must error like
// `type D = D`, not merely warn until used).
//
// This used to be an `empty-intersection` WARNING that fired only when the alias
// was used; it is now the never-value ERROR at the declaration, regardless of
// use. The `empty-intersection` lint therefore no longer fires for a `type`
// alias (the error supersedes it — no duplicate diagnostic); the lint still
// covers annotated variable bindings.
//
// The operand description is accurate — `A` is `{ a: string }` ("an object") and
// `B` is `"foo"` ("a string literal"), NOT "a number literal" (PR #189 review).
// The error RANGE covers the `A & B` intersection EXPRESSION (0-indexed `19:9`,
// the `type C = A & B` annotation), not the alias name `C`.
type A = { a: string }
type B = "foo"
type C = A & B
print(1)
